{"slug": "conjurer", "root": "conjurer", "category": "profession", "gloss": "a summoner of spirits", "definition": "A conjurer summons spirits and binds them to obedience, commanding demons or angels to appear within a circle and do his bidding. Where a *necromancer* questions the dead and a *diviner* reads signs, the conjurer compels a present spirit face to face. By the 1500s the same word also named the stage-trickster who only seems to.", "history": "The word comes from Latin *coniurare*, 'to swear together' — a conspiracy of oaths. Ritual magic kept that oath-logic literal: the conjurer binds a spirit not by force but by adjuration, swearing it into compliance with divine names, exactly as an exorcist commands a demon. Kieckhefer notes the conjurer's stance was at once coercive and petitionary, half-command, half-prayer. The turn came in the sixteenth century, when 'conjurer' split: Reginald Scot could call the pope an 'arch-conjurer,' while the same word slid toward the fairground illusionist. Both senses survive, and Magic uses the older one — a caller of spirits.", "def_sources": [{"label": "Kieckhefer, Magic in the Middle Ages", "where": "Medieval magic (PDF)"}, {"label": "Klaassen, The Transformations of Magic", "where": "Medieval magic (PDF)"}, {"label": "Etymonline, s.v. conjure (Latin coniurare)", "where": "Etymology reference"}], "is_keyword": false, "etymology": {"lang": "Latin", "origin": "Latin coniurare 'to swear together'", "first": "c. 1400; 'stage magician' by 1580s", "note": "One who binds spirits by oath — and, by the 1500s, the street-performer who only seems to. Both senses survive.", "hook": "When 'conjurer' split into sorcerer and street-magician."}, "essay": null, "sources": ["Etymonline (Douglas Harper)", "Wiktionary", "classical lexica (Lewis & Short, LSJ, Bosworth–Toller)", "Ted's historical-magic DBs (WitchcraftStudiesDB, AgrippaDOP, MedievalMagicDB)"], "stats": {"flavor_total": 2, "oracle_total": 2, "in_flavor_cards": 2, "in_oracle_c